Similarly to the others, I'm iffy about this.

+block

–block


From a tone and style standpoint, this is very well written. I actually like the picture.

But when you consider the story of this object, all that's present is  The logs don't do much except for spell out details already known from the description and provide fairly bland alien vistas. The only notable action is the occasional loss of D-Class, and the only payoff you're building up to is the animal attack.

My usual critique is that logs that spell out how things already known in the description are a waste of space. Logs are for building tension, advancing the narrative, and adding interesting or evocative details. Your logs are well written, that's a strength for you, but they aren't in service of anything super-compelling. Other portals-to-worlds tell us interesting stories about those other worlds and the things or people in them (the red sea object, the window with red and blue men,), or the way the Foundationverse works (there's a  universe portal that turns out isn't quite a mirror), or the way the Foundation treats such things (the paddling pool). Stories can be about the actions of characters, or creators, or the Foundation, or even just the description of what the object does can be a story.

On a purely technical level, this is probably the best written wornhole skip I can think of, but sadly that just isn't as important. You've got to have a story you want to tell, and tell it in an interesting and intentional way. That, or imagery so wild or knocks people's socks off. This is really weak on both fronts.




So -1 from me. I like your writing and look forward to your future skips, but be sure to keep storytelling firmly in mind.







